<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-493-811  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 493 811.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Fal 1990 v15 n11 p121(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical storage primer.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harvey, David A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Optical data storage is here to stay, but the user shouldunderstand the functioning, advantages and disadvantages of eachoptical storage technology.andP;  There are three major opticaltechnologies: CD-ROM, WORM (write once/read many) and erasable(typically called magneto-optical).andP;  All three use coherent light,usually a semiconductor laser, to read and write data to themedia.andP;  CD-ROM is strictly a 'publishing' media, providing up to660Mbytes of data on one disk.andP;  WORM disks can be written to once,read as often as desired, but not erased.andP;  Erasable (orrewritable) magneto-optical drives employ a semiconductor laser tochange the coercivity of the recording media and the magneticorientation of the particles.andP;  Details of each technology, impactson MS-DOS, and market outlook are also discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical MemoryWORMMagneto-Optical Disk DrivesCD-ROMSpecificationsOutlookTrends.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>